# Architecture Decision Rules: Data Access & Backend Logic

You are an expert in Next.js App Router (RSC), Drizzle on Neon Postgres, Better
Auth, and Vercel runtime primitives. Use these guidelines to choose the right
pattern for any new data access or backend logic.

## Stack at a glance

| Layer | Tech |
| --- | --- |
| Rendering | Next.js App Router, React Server Components |
| Auth | Better Auth — Route Handlers via `@/server/api/auth`, RSC via `@/lib/auth/server-session` |
| DB | Drizzle ORM on Neon Postgres (`@app/db`) |
| Storage | Cloudflare R2 (`@/server/lib/r2`); GCS (`@/server/lib/gcs`) for Gemini video-insight only |
| AI | Vercel AI SDK v6 + AI Gateway (`@ai-sdk/react`, `ai`) |
| Cache / rate-limit / idempotency | Upstash Redis via `@/server/lib/redis` (REST) |
| Background work | Vercel Queues (`/api/queues/*`), Vercel Cron (`/api/cron/*`) |
| Realtime | SSE under `/api/realtime/*` backed by ioredis (`REDIS_URL`) for pub/sub |
| Hosting | Vercel Functions (Fluid Compute, Node.js runtime) |

## The four primary patterns

| Pattern | Path | Use case | Latency | Complexity |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| **RSC + Server Loader** | `src/server/loaders/*.ts` | Server-rendered reads of the user's own data | Lowest | Lowest |
| **Route Handler** | `src/app/api/**/route.ts` | Client-callable APIs, AI streaming, webhooks, cron, queues, SSE | Medium | Medium |
| **Server Handler module** | `src/server/handlers/*.ts` | Business logic shared by routes/queues; transactions, side effects | Medium | Higher |
| **Queue / Cron Worker** | `src/app/api/queues/*` and `src/app/api/cron/*` | Async / scheduled / long-running work | N/A (async) | Higher |

A typical request fans out: **Route Handler** (auth + parse) → **Server Handler**
(business logic / transactions) → **Drizzle** (DB) → **Server Loader** (only on
the next render to read back state).

---

## Pattern 1: RSC + Server Loader

`src/server/loaders/*.ts` exports plain async functions that run inside Server
Components and SSR pages, read directly from Drizzle, and return DTOs.

### Use when

1. **User reads their own data on a server-rendered page**
2. **Listing / detail views with no side effects**
3. **You can place ownership / soft-delete checks at the page level**

```typescript
// src/server/loaders/gen-task-history.ts
import { and, desc, eq, isNull } from 'drizzle-orm';
import { getDbHttp } from '@app/db';
import { genTasks } from '@app/db/schema';
import { genTaskRowToDto } from '@/server/dto/gen-task';

export async function listGenTasksForHistory(input: {
  uid: string;
  limit: number;
  offset: number;
}) {
  const db = getDbHttp();
  const rows = await db
    .select()
    .from(genTasks)
    .where(and(eq(genTasks.uid, input.uid), isNull(genTasks.deletedAt)))
    .orderBy(desc(genTasks.createdAt))
    .limit(input.limit)
    .offset(input.offset);
  return rows.map(genTaskRowToDto);
}
```

```typescript
// src/app/[locale]/app/(features)/projects/page.tsx (RSC)
import { redirect } from 'next/navigation';
import { getCurrentUser } from '@/lib/auth/server-session';
import { listGenTasksForHistory } from '@/server/loaders/gen-task-history';

export default async function Page() {
  const user = await getCurrentUser();
  if (!user) redirect('/auth/login');

  const tasks = await listGenTasksForHistory({ uid: user.uid, limit: 20, offset: 0 });
  return <TaskList tasks={tasks} />;
}
```

### Don't use when

- The browser needs to call it directly (use a Route Handler).
- It writes data or has side effects (use a Server Handler behind a Route
  Handler).
- It crosses users / needs admin scope without explicit gating.

